This might be a little early to recommend this, but it would be interesting to follow-up this series with a mini-course on Comparative Vertebrate Morphology.  It's not a widely-known discipline, but it takes the principles you learn in A&P and expands them to other vertebrate taxa, exploring things like why cheetahs and gazelles have the same basic body type, why frogs have three-chambered hearts, why kangaroos have three holes "down under", and why a shark's kidney is about half the length of its body.  A lot of CVM topics especially help to elucidate why the human body is shaped the way it is and functions the way it does.
